Explanation and reasoning

- I inspected app/Http/Controllers/Api/V1/PostController.php. The show(Post $post) method returns new PostResource($post). That is the method that will be used for GET /v1/posts/{post}. The destroy method deletes the post and returns a no-content response, but it is not used for GET; the relevant code for GET is the show method.
- I inspected the resource shaping code in app/Http/Resources/Post.php (JsonResource). The toArray() method defines the JSON shape returned for a single Post resource. The returned fields (and inferred types) are:
  - id: integer
  - title: string
  - slug: string
  - content: string
  - posted_at: string (ISO8601 date/time)
  - author_id: integer
  - comments_count: integer
  - thumbnail_url: string (URL) — returned conditionally only if the post has a thumbnail
  - thumb_thumbnail_url: string (URL) — returned conditionally only if the post has a thumbnail
- Laravel route model binding will return a 404 Not Found if the {post} does not exist, so include a 404 response entry.
- I therefore produce a Swagger 2.0 "responses" dictionary for GET /v1/posts/{post} including:
  - 200: Successful response with a schema matching the PostResource fields above.
  - 404: Not found response with a simple schema containing a message string (Laravel's JSON error responses include a message field).

